h3. Problem Definition
There is currently no variable for pull request hashes.
h3. Suggested Solution
Add a Bamboo variable, such as $\{bamboo.repository.pullRequest}
h3. Workaround
As a workaround, you can use your version control system's API. Below are examples of possible GitHub and Bitbucket Server API calls.
h4. GitHub
{code:title=API call}curl -s -u<username>:<personal-access-token> https://api.github.com/repos/<owner>/<repository>/pulls | grep merge_commit_sha|awk -F'"' '{print $4}'{code}
h4. Bitbucket Server
{code:title=API call}curl -s -u<username>:<pasword> "<bitbucket-url>/rest/api/1.0/projects/<project-key>/repos/<repo-slug>/pull-requests"|json_pp|grep 'latestCommit\|Ref'
Enter host password for user 'ezeidan':
         "toRef" : {
            "latestCommit" : "9f99052b726d18a3c8d62ba9e02f0d09519bedfa",
         "fromRef" : {
            "latestCommit" : "92006c7ce897a0fb4d8faacd7a0d79d887728925",
{code}

h2. HTR
Consider the following code:
{code}
        final BitbucketCloudRepository bitbucketRepository = new BitbucketCloudRepository()
                .name("repo")
                .repositorySlug("owner", "repository")
                .branch("master");

        final GitRepository gitRepository = new GitRepository()
                .name("repo")
                .url("file:///tmp/repository");
        
        bambooServer.publish(gitRepository);
        bambooServer.publish(bitbucketRepository);
{code}

h2. Expected behaviour

Bamboo gives meaningful error message about linked repository name uniqueness and the name clash.

h2. Actual behaviour

Bamboo gives cryptic error message:
{noformat}
Exception in thread "main" com.atlassian.bamboo.specs.api.exceptions.BambooSpecsPublishingException: An error occurred while publishing repository repo: Repository type can not be changed. Was: com.atlassian.bamboo.plugins.atlassian-bamboo-plugin-git:gitv2, new: com.atlassian.bamboo.plugins.atlassian-bamboo-plugin-bitbucket:bbCloud
{noformat}

h3. Summary
Risks of migration and upgrade failure due to property (e.g {color:blue}<buildNumber />{color}) being stored in {color:blue}<bamboo-home>/bamboo.cfg.xml{color} filesystem instead of database.

h3. Scenario
The property in question is responsible to let Bamboo know which upgrade tasks should be executed during the startup process. Lets review the following scenario:
* Bamboo version A (_connected to Production database_)
{color:blue}<buildNumber>123456</buildNumber>{color}
{color:blue}<property name="hibernate.connection.url">jdbc:mysql://localhost/bambooPROD?autoReconnect=true</property>{color}
* Bamboo version B (_new installation_)
{color:blue}<buildNumber>999999</buildNumber>{color}
{color:blue}<property name="hibernate.connection.url">jdbc:mysql://localhost/bambooTEMP?autoReconnect=true</property>{color}

When upgrading Bamboo (_from version A to version B_) administrators *must not* edit {color:blue}<bamboo-home>/bamboo.cfg.xml{color} from new Bamboo installation (_version B_)  to point to the Bamboo's database (_production data_) because the {color:blue}<buildNumber>999999</buildNumber>{color} in the new installation is more recent than version A.

h3. Suggestion 
Some properties (e.g {color:blue}<buildNumber />{color}) in {color:blue}<bamboo-home>/bamboo.cfg.xml{color} should be moved/stored in the database, minimising the risks of  unsuccessful Bamboo's migration or upgrade.

h3. Summary
When viewing a Plan using the {{ArtifactDownloaderTask}} as Bamboo Specs, the {{ArtifactDownloaderTask}} HLL representation is incorrect.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a Bamboo Plan
# Add an Artifact Download Task
# Go to {{Actions >> View as Bamboo Specs}}

h3. Expected Results
According to the [Bamboo Specs Reference|https://docs.atlassian.com/bamboo-specs-docs/latest/?_ga=2.229306204.1147488184.1498486833-2142414282.1490120791#task-artifact-downloader], the code should be:
{code}DownloadItem downloadAllArtifacts = new DownloadItem()
    .allArtifacts(true);
DownloadItem downloadSpecificArtifact = new DownloadItem()
    .artifact("an artifact")
    .path("subdirectory");
PlanIdentifier planIdentifier = new PlanIdentifier("PROJECTKEY", "PLANKEY");
ArtifactDownloaderTask artifactDownloaderTask = new ArtifactDownloaderTask()
    .description("My artifact downloader task")
    .sourcePlan(planIdentifier)
    .artifacts(downloadAllArtifacts, downloadSpecificArtifact);{code}

h3. Actual Results
The below code is output in the View as Bamboo Specs page:
{code}
new ArtifactDownloaderTask()
    .sourcePlan(new PlanIdentifier()
        .key(new BambooKey("PROJECTKEY"))
        .projectKey(new BambooKey("PLANKEY")))
{code}
 

h3.Workaround
h4. Option 1
Use one of the following formats instead:
 {code}
new ArtifactDownloaderTask()
    .sourcePlan(new PlanIdentifier(new BambooKey("PROJECTKEY"), new BambooKey("PLANKEY")))
{code}

 {code}
new ArtifactDownloaderTask()
    .sourcePlan(new PlanIdentifier("PROJECTKEY", "PLANKEY"))
{code}

h4. Option 2
Copy the output code, and update the Artifact Downloader Task to use the format suggested by the Bamboo Specs documentation.

{code}Plan createPlan() {
    return new Plan(
        project(),
            "Plan Name", "PLANKEY")
            .description("My test plan")
            .stages(new Stage("Default Stage")
                .jobs(new Job("Job 1", new BambooKey("JOB1"))
                   .tasks(artifactDownloaderTask)
                )
             )
        );
}         

DownloadItem downloadAllArtifacts = new DownloadItem()
    .allArtifacts(true);
DownloadItem downloadSpecificArtifact = new DownloadItem()
    .artifact("an artifact")
    .path("subdirectory");
PlanIdentifier planIdentifier = new PlanIdentifier("PROJECTKEY", "PLANKEY");
ArtifactDownloaderTask artifactDownloaderTask = new ArtifactDownloaderTask()
    .description("My artifact downloader task")
    .sourcePlan(planIdentifier)
    .artifacts(downloadAllArtifacts, downloadSpecificArtifact);{code}
